<DOC><DOCNO> AP890807-0055 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-07-89 0706EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Weather     08-07 0331</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Japan-Weather,0341</SECOND><HEAD>Typhoon, Earthquake Hit Japan; Eight Dead</HEAD><DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Tropical Storm Mac swept across northern Japanduring the night, triggering floods and landslides that killedeight people and left seven others missing, police said today.   The storm hit Fukushima Prefecture on Sunday. Today, anearthquake measuring 5.6 on the Richter scale hit Hokkaido, butthere were no immediate reports of damage or injuries.   The earthquake was centered in the ocean near Kushiro, in theeastern part of Hokkaido island about 530 miles northeast of Tokyo,according to the Central Meteorological Agency. It said there wasno danger of a tsunami, the dangerous wave sometimes caused byearthquakes.   Six people died Sunday when a 98-foot-long bridge collapsed in aflooded river and three cars carrying a total of 11 people plungedinto the muddy stream, said an official with the FukushimaPrefectural police who spoke on condition of anonymity.   He said the other five still were missing.   ``Water is all over the place, and we can no longer tell wherethe river used to flow,'' said another police official.   A 23-year-old man died when he fell into a flood-swollen riverelsewhere in Fukushima and a 53-year-old housewife was buried by alandslide, the first official added.   He said a 52-year-old man disappeared while helping firefightersrepair the banks of a river in Fukushima, and a seventh person wasmissing in Miyagi prefecture just north of Fukushima.   The storm also left 15 people injured, including 11 inFukushima, about 150 miles northeast of Tokyo, he said.   He said 12 houses were destroyed, 4,042 houses were flooded,roads were destroyed at 88 places, bridges were damaged at 21 andlandslides occurred at 108 places.   The storm, listed as typhoon No. 13 as it approached Japan, hadweakened to a tropical storm by the time it hit Choshi, in Chiba,with winds of 68 mph Sunday afternoon.   The storm was off Japan's northernmost main island of Hokkaidotonight, the Meteorological Agency said.</TEXT></DOC>